Taxonomic history. For more than a century this species has been most familiar under the incorrect name
C. rhizophorarum
(here shown to be a distinct species, endemic to the Philippines ). The name
C. moerchii
was not, however, forgotten. In the Ryukyu Islands and Taiwan the shells are small with coarse ribs, and
C. moerchii
was based on this form. Early Japanese authors identified the larger mainland form as
C. rhizophorarum
and used
C. moerchii
for the smaller island form, considering it to be a distinct species (
Iwakawa 1919
;
Kuroda 1928
;
Hirase 1934
;
Kuroda & Habe 1952
;
Oyama 1959
;
Higo et al . 1999
) or subspecies (
Habe & Kosuge 1967
;
Habe 1968
;
Higo 1973
;
Okutani 1986
;
Higo & Goto 1993
). More recently,
C. moerchii
has been considered only a “geographical form” (
Hasegawa 2000 : 133
) and this was supported by the lack of genetic differentiation between samples from mainland Japan and the Ryukyu Islands (
Kojima et al . 2006
;
Reid et al . 2008
, 2013 ). The name
C. rhizophorarum
has since been widely applied in Japan , China , Korea and Vietnam (e.g.
Ma 2004
;
Min et al . 2004
;
Thach 2007
;
Zhang 2008
; Kimura & Fukuda 2012 ;
Li & Huang 2012
), but
C. moerchii
has now been reinstated as the valid name for this species (
Reid et al . 2013
).

